76561198032632811,Recommended,233150,31887425,Posted: 21 May,all,CasualCheetah,"Luftrausers was a pleasant surprise. I started out with almost no idea of what the game was except for a few screenshots and mentions that gave it high praise.The relatively unintuitive controls for flying around ended up being a thrill and give just enough direct control to make it feel like you really are narrowly boosting in and out of swarms of enemy fights. The catchy music and brown stain palette do an amazing job of creating an ‘against all odds’/WW2 dogfight game feel that also complements the insanity the game can throw at you sometimes. Moving from blasting fighters while freefalling to boosting away from a mass of projectiles, waiting for your ship to repair, before you boost right back into the crowd feels exhilarating.The customizations are interesting ways to keep you entertained while you complete mini-objectives but they can seem pretty useless if you already have a preferred setup for your plane. Since the arcade-like nature of the game prefers to have you improve your skill, none of the customizations are straight upgrades and all have downsides but it helps to keep the game interesting over the long run, especially as you find uniquely volatile combinations for beating certain enemies or mini-objectives.That being said, the enemy variety gets old rather fast and you can experience what feels like a majority of the game in only a few hours. This feeling is amplified after running out of do-able mini-objectives (dang some of them are tough/rare). It’s the same handful of remixes and 5 or 6 enemy types every round, and I don’t get the feeling that things really change after defeating the blimp (which almost never appears).Still, it’s a captivating game for the first couple hours and is something you’ll spend a lot of time revisiting."
