,Recommended,233150,17785798,"Posted: 29 August, 2015",all,Graced by Autumn,"Vlambeer: a studio known for its outstanding design skills and dedication to retro-inspired games that deliver fast action without getting hung up on anything that isn’t directly related to the core gameplay. This studio has proven itself time and time again with its catalogue of fast-action games. It should therefore come as no surprise to one acquainted with the two-man team’s previous releases that LUFTRAUSERS is a game of the same variety. It should also come as no surprise to hear that; like those games; it is also an undoubtedly outstanding piece of work.The core gameplay of LUFTRAUSERS is centred on the destruction of enemy aircraft, naval vessels and blimps (the latter of which only appear once you’re scoring big). Like other shmups LUFTRAUSERS likes to throw wave after wave of enemies at you. In this case there’s a little more room to manoeuvre than what one might be used to in a bog-standard shmup. It’s possible to scroll the screen left or right and continue flying in either direction indefinitely as you contend with the limitless supply of opponents for your blood. Destroying enemies earns the player points and as one’s score increases so too does the severity of the threat posed by the enemy. Each time an enemy is killed, the player’s score multiplier goes up by one. Keeping that multiplier high is the key to getting the best scores. It’s a very simple concept, but it lends itself to create some interesting gameplay scenarios. Do you go chase down that swarm of fighters in order to raise your multiplier before sinking the nearby battleship? Or do you attack the ship first and take the fighters on afterwards? The former has the potential to yield a greater final score, but it’s worth bearing in mind that dodging AA fire is no joke. The latter is the safer option, but you’re not going to get as many points that way. Players just starting out are likely to only witness some fighters and gun boats, but those racking up big scores will quickly find themselves facing off against large numbers of battleships, aircraft equipped with laser weapons and eventually the dreaded blimps. Stronger enemies yield more points, so the more of them you kill the better your score becomes, but that comes at the expense of inviting further trouble in the form of more of those strong enemies showing up to blow you out of the sky (whichwillhappen sooner or later, as is the case with games featuring what one might call ‘survival-mode’ style gameplay).A Rauser is comprised of three components: a weapon, body and engine. Specific components from each category can be swapped in and out upon returning to the menus, allowing you to find a perfect match that suits your playstyle. Some of the available choices are fairly conventional, while others are somewhat less so. Want to fly a jet with a conventional machine gun built into the nose? Fine. What about a plane that propels itself through the sky by firing bullets from its tail-end, while incinerating those in front of it with a high-powered laser? It’s done. Or maybe an aircraft that can dive under the waves and surface under enemy ships, sinking them with a single-shot cannon that releases additional projectiles in all directions after the initial projectile’s impact? Not a problem. Every part has a number of small-scale tasks associated with it, such as defeating a certain number of enemies whilst maintaining a combo, or killing enough enemies of a specific type. Successfully completing these tasks usually unlocks either new parts or new colour schemes. Most of these short-term goals are fun to pursue and encourage a bit of experimentation. Even if you have a favourite combination of parts, it’s fun to go after some of these while trying out parts which you might not normally go for.The world of LUFTRAUSERS is depicted through pixel art, something that a good number of indie games have chosen to go for. The visual style goes a long way in contributing towards the ‘arcade-like’ feel that the game has - a retro-inspired art style for a retro-inspired game. The default colour scheme keeps things simple enough so that it’s always easy to keep track of what’s going on, while the effective use of silhouettes in place of highly detailed sprites allows your imagination to fill in the blanks. Some of the alternate colour schemes are less appealing, thanks to some colour combinations that just don’t match-up, either because the contrast between colours is too great or because the scheme feels dull in comparison to the default one.KOZILEK’s main theme fits the game well enough, but what really stands out here is how the instruments used to play the said theme change depending on which parts you’ve got equipped. It’s a nice little touch that keeps things fresh. The sound effects themselves also do a great job of helping to maintain that retro feel, and sound like they came straight out of an 8-bit game.LUFTRAUSERS is another example of a game made by a studio that knows its target audience inside-out. It’s a stellar example of an arcade-style game done right – it knows it’s a straightforward, pick-up-and-play game, so it focuses purely on what matters most for that type of game: the core gameplay experience. Put simply if you’re a fan of the ‘instant-action’ games that Vlambeer has put out in the past then chances are LUFTRAUSERS is one game you can’t afford to miss out on."
,Recommended,233150,9557626,"Posted: 18 March, 2014",all,Tegiminis,"Yes, I recommend this game."
76561198045133849,Recommended,233150,9558643,"Posted: 19 March, 2014",all,BarneyRound,Wow. Addicting.Edit: Very addicting
76561198079072229,Recommended,233150,22245788,"Posted: 4 April, 2016",all,Sir Squidington,"SummaryLustrausers is an enjoyable 2D shooter that, while simple in princaple, takes a hell od a lot of skill. Some of the challenges are unarguably unfare.More in-depthLuftrausers (also known as LoveTrousers) is a difficult little arcady shoot-'em-up where you control one of over 100 diffrent planes, knowns as rausers. By mixing and maching 6 diffrent parts in 3 catagories (weapon,body,engine) you can design a rausers to meet your specifi needs and goal. What are those needs and goals? To blow up everything in the sea and sky!The focus of the game to complete various missions assigned to each part and to gain new highscores. These missions range from ""destroy your fist X"" to ""score X amount"" or ""get X number of kills in a single combo"" and can become significantly difficult to accomplish.Your score isheavlydependant of building, maintaining, and killing powerfull enimies in combos. after killing an enemy, your multiplier will apear, starting at x1 and increasing by 1 every kill, to a max of x20. While you can kill wimpy enimies to gain huge combos, the challenge and reward lies in killing the toughest enimies while keeping your combo up and not dieing.How about a list of pros and cons?+ Huge diversity of possible combinations+ Unique parts to your rauser, each with it's own benifit and weakness+ No two parts are polar opposites: one body gives health at the cost of speed, while another lacks healthbut can ram through enemies no problem+ Soundtrack that changes to mach your current build+ The unique movement of your rauser allows you to stall and float through the air, allowing you to deal with all those pesky fighters on your tail without changing direction+ TONS or replayability, because you may survive between 5 seconds and 5 minuets+ you can ram boats and planes to blow them up and dive your plane underwater! How cool is that?+ Challenging missions- Challenging missions relying on the random number genorator to spawn key enemies, especialy when you need to kill that [Classified No.1]- Random nuber genorator willscrewyou over and over with ridiculous enemy spawns- The diffuculty of some missions will likley be what make you leave the game behind, with some of the last missions being nigh impossible, especialy the unofficsl the last 1 missionscore over 25000 in SFMT (the super mega hard mode)- The big, high health enemies will kill enemy spawns, making it highly difficult to keep your combos- Almost too much importance placed on combos: enemies give small numbers of points, and the combos are needed to make any progress- Some bugs and exploitsAll in all, I recomend it, but prepare to be frusterated more and more the longer you play the game until it gets close to being an unenjoyable chore."
