,Recommended,233150,24248217,"Posted: 11 July, 2016",all,CaptBananas,"The most effective praise that I can give for 'LUFTRAUSERS' is that it is simply crafted, yet because of its simplicity it is wildly addictive.It has been a good long time since I've had a game hook me so quickly with its combination of a fantastic soundtrack, pleasant visuals, and easy to pick up & go gameplay.Every single aspect of the game is finely honed and effective.Before I'd even realized it, an hour plus had passed and I was just itching to launch my newest version of my plane and do battle in the skies once more.Let me be clear about something however -- I am not a young gamer.I am firmly from the generation that favored gameplay over graphics, and I still hold that aspect close to my heart.And that is why I believe 'LUFTRAUSERS' resonates so deeply with me.It reminds me of days gone past of NES games like 'Air Fortress' (in the Air Base phase, at least), 'Raiden', and even as early as ATARI's 'Tempest', except in this new age of games 'LUFTRAUSERS' brings all of that nostalgia to the table & adds a pulse-pounding soundtrack as well as other current gaming tropes.Another thing to note is the difficulty of the game -- it's elevated enough that I can imagine it turning off gamers from a younger generation, but it's a welcome inclusion for me -- as (in my opinion) too many games today trade in difficulty for excessive content.All said & done, I would HIGHLY recommend 'LUFTRAUSERS' to anyone who can appreciate a game that is able to bring many classic 'flight' & 'shoot 'em up' ideas all together into one cohesive package.EDIT 11/26/2016: Nominated for the Steam(y) Awards under the category 'Best Indie Bullethell with an Amazing Soundtrack'."
